---
description: Schema and field conventions for all event records
globs: ["app/events.py", "tests/test_event_detection.py"]
---

# Event Record Fields

Every event dict passed to the DB must contain exactly these keys:
  city, event_type, severity, description, timestamp, triggered_at, reading_id, details

- event_type: snake_case string, one of:
    temperature_spike | temperature_plunge | precipitation_onset |
    high_wind | severe_weather_code | feels_like_divergence
- severity: one of "info" | "warning" | "critical"
- description: human-readable, must include the city name and the measured values that triggered the event
- details: JSON string — must include the specific numeric values used in detection logic (for auditability)
- timestamp: the reading's timestamp (when weather occurred)
- triggered_at: UTC ISO8601 (when the service detected it)

# Threshold Config

All city-specific thresholds live in CITY_CONFIG in app/events.py.
Never hardcode numeric thresholds inside detection functions — always reference CITY_CONFIG[city].

# Anti-spam

For events that can persist across readings (high_wind, precipitation), check the last event
of that type for that city before firing. Do not fire a duplicate event if the condition
was already active in the previous reading.
